	<p class="cs709C557D"><span class="cs8498B7A6">WEST VIRGINIA LEGISLATURE</span></p><p class="cs1CE9D70E"><span class="csB0C9F1E0">2026 </span><span class="csC2FEE544">REGULAR SESSION</span></p><p class="cs63FD752D" style="tab-stops:center 234pt left 402pt;"><span class="csC2FEE544">	Introduced	</span><div style="width:49pt;height:32pt;border-width:0.5pt;border-style:solid;border-color:Black;background-color:#FFFFFF;margin:0pt 9pt 0pt 9pt;padding:5pt 0pt 0pt 0pt;">
		<p class="csAC81313F"><span class="cs4457F601">FISCAL NOTE</span></p></div>
	</p><p class="cs3E63B65"><span class="cs8498B7A6">House Bill 5601</span></p><p class="csFF933113"><span class="csADC6E5DB">By Delegate Green</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">[Introduced February 16, 2026; referred to the Committee on House Government OrganizationGovernment Organization]</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">A BILL</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> making a supplementary appropriation from the Governor&rsquo;s Office &ndash; Civil Contingent Fund to the Governor&rsquo;s Office &ndash; Office of Resiliency for deposit into the West Virginia Disaster Recovery Trust Fund; and amending the Code of West Virginia, 1931, as amended, by adding a new section designated &sect;29-31-7a, relating to disaster case management grants administered through the West Virginia Disaster Recovery Trust Fund; requiring competitive award; establishing eligibility requiring a brick-and-mortar presence and operational capacity in West Virginia; requiring coordination with Long-Term Recovery Organizations; setting reporting and accountability requirements; and providing an effective date.</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">Be it enacted by the Legislature of West Virginia:</span></p><h2 class="cs256F29A0">
		<span class="csCD0B21F9">ARTICLE 1. SUPPLEMENTARY APPROPRIATION FOR DISASTER CASE MANAGEMENT.</span></h2>
	<p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">SECTION 1. Appropriation; transfer; required deposit to trust fund.</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">Whereas</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">, The Governor submitted the Executive Budget Document to the Legislature, including the State Fund, General Revenue; and</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">Whereas</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">, The Legislature finds that a public purpose exists to strengthen long-term disaster recovery for West Virginians through professional disaster case management services coordinated with local recovery partners; therefore,</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">Be it enacted by the Legislature of West Virginia</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">, That the items of appropriation set forth below are hereby made for the fiscal year ending June 30, 2026:</span></p><h3 class="cs256F29A0">
		<span class="cs96E14A57">TITLE II &mdash; APPROPRIATIONS.</span></h3>
	<h4 class="cs256F29A0">
		<span class="cs4457F601">Section 1. Appropriations from General Revenue.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">7 &mdash; Governor&rsquo;s Office &mdash; Civil Contingent Fund</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"><br/></span><span class="cs57AFC0BC">(W. Va. Code Chapter 5)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"><br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">Fund 0105 FY 2026 Org 0100</span></p><ol start="1" style="margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;">
		<li class="csB1511CCF"><span class="cs4457F601">Local Economic Development Assistance (R) (Appropriation 81900)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> is hereby </span><span class="cs4457F601">decreased</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> by </span><span class="cs4457F601">$1,000,000</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">. </span></li></ol>
	<p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">5 &mdash; Governor&rsquo;s Office &mdash; Office of Resiliency</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"><br/></span><span class="cs57AFC0BC">(W. Va. Code Chapter 5)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"><br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">Fund 0101 FY 2026 Org 0100</span></p><ol start="1" style="margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;">
		<li class="csB1511CCF"><span class="cs4457F601">Office of Resiliency (R) (Appropriation 18600)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> is hereby </span><span class="cs4457F601">increased</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> by </span><span class="cs4457F601">$1,000,000</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">. </span></li></ol>
	<p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">Provided, That</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> the entire $1,000,000 increase provided in this section shall be </span><span class="cs4457F601">deposited and credited</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> by the State Resiliency Officer into the </span><span class="cs4457F601">West Virginia Disaster Recovery Trust Fund</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> established pursuant to </span><span class="cs4457F601">&sect;29-31-6</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> of this code and administered pursuant to </span><span class="cs4457F601">&sect;29-31-7</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> of this code, and shall be </span><span class="cs4457F601">separately accounted for</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> and </span><span class="cs4457F601">used exclusively</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> for the disaster case management purposes set forth in </span><span class="cs4457F601">&sect;29-31-7a</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">, as added by this bill. </span></p><h2 class="cs256F29A0">
		<span class="csCD0B21F9">ARTICLE 2. DISASTER CASE MANAGEMENT GRANTS THROUGH THE DISASTER RECOVERY TRUST FUND.</span></h2>
	<p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">SECTION 2. The Code of West Virginia, 1931, as amended, is amended by adding thereto a new section, designated &sect;29-31-7a, to read as follows:</span></p><h3 class="cs256F29A0">
		<span class="cs96E14A57">&sect;29-31-7a. Disaster case management grants; competitive awards; West Virginia presence; coordination with Long-Term Recovery Organizations.</span></h3>
	<p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(a) Purpose.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash; The Legislature finds that disaster recovery timelines commonly extend for months and years and that households often require hands-on support to access federal, state, local, philanthropic, and nonprofit recovery resources. Therefore, the purpose of this section is to authorize the State Resiliency Officer to use moneys deposited into the West Virginia Disaster Recovery Trust Fund for </span><span class="cs4457F601">professional disaster case management services</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> to assist affected West Virginians in both </span><span class="cs4457F601">declared</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> and </span><span class="cs4457F601">undeclared</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> disaster events, consistent with the priorities and conditions applicable to the Disaster Recovery Trust Fund. </span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(b) Definition.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash; For purposes of this section, &ldquo;disaster case management&rdquo; means time-limited, structured support to disaster-impacted households, including: (1) intake and needs assessment; (2) development of a recovery plan; (3) assistance applying for and appealing FEMA or other disaster determinations; (4) navigation of housing, repair, essential-needs, and benefit programs; (5) coordination of referrals and documentation; and (6) transition from crisis response to stable recovery.</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(c) Competitive grant process required.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash;<br/>(1) The State Resiliency Officer shall award grants </span><span class="cs4457F601">competitively</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> to one or more eligible organizations to provide disaster case management services in West Virginia.<br/>(2) The State Resiliency Officer may award grants on a statewide, regional, or disaster-event basis and may renew or extend awards based on performance and continued need.<br/>(3) The State Resiliency Officer may require cost reasonableness, standardized reporting, and outcome-based performance measures as conditions of award.</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(d) Eligibility; West Virginia brick-and-mortar presence and operational capacity.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash;<br/>(1) To be eligible for a grant under this section, an organization shall demonstrate all of the following:<br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">(A)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> A </span><span class="cs4457F601">bona fide physical office location (brick-and-mortar presence) in West Virginia</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">, available for public-facing service delivery or program administration;<br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">(B)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> </span><span class="cs4457F601">Operational capacity in West Virginia</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">, which shall include, at a minimum, the ability to deploy and supervise case managers serving West Virginia households, including WV-based staff or contractors and established service-delivery systems; and<br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">(C)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> Experience providing disaster recovery services, human services case management, or closely related recovery navigation services, as determined by the State Resiliency Officer.<br/>(2) </span><span class="cs4457F601">An organization is not required to be headquartered in West Virginia</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> to be eligible under this section: </span><span class="cs4457F601">Provided, That</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> it satisfies the physical presence and operational capacity requirements of subdivision (1) of this subsection.</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(e) Coordination with Long-Term Recovery Organizations.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash;<br/>(1) A grantee shall coordinate its disaster case management activities with local or regional </span><span class="cs4457F601">Long-Term Recovery Organizations (LTROs)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E">, long-term recovery groups, unmet needs committees, VOAD partners, or substantially similar recovery coalitions serving the affected area.<br/>(2) The State Resiliency Officer shall require documentation of coordination as a condition of award, which may include memoranda of understanding, letters of coordination, referral pathways, meeting participation, or other evidence acceptable to the State Resiliency Officer.</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(f) Allowable uses; staffing.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash; Funds awarded under this section may be used for case management staffing and supervision, training, travel for deployment within West Virginia, outreach and intake, client documentation systems, and other direct program costs necessary to deliver disaster case management services: </span><span class="cs4457F601">Provided, That</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> funds may not be used for unrelated general fundraising or activities not connected to disaster case management delivery in West Virginia.</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(g) Reporting; accountability; records.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash;<br/>(1) Grantees shall report at least quarterly, in a form prescribed by the State Resiliency Officer, including:<br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">(A)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> households served and counties served;<br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">(B)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> types of assistance accessed (including FEMA and other programs);<br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">(C)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> estimated dollars leveraged or benefits accessed for households, where practicable;<br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">(D)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> timeliness measures and case outcomes; and<br/></span><span class="cs4457F601">(E)</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> coordination activities with LTROs.<br/>(2) Grantees shall maintain records for inspection and audit and shall comply with any applicable state grant requirements and the disbursement conditions applicable to the Disaster Recovery Trust Fund.</span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(h) Relationship to existing trust fund law.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash; Moneys expended under this section shall be administered as disbursements from the West Virginia Disaster Recovery Trust Fund and shall remain subject to the priorities and conditions of </span><span class="cs4457F601">&sect;29-31-7</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> of this code, including prioritization for low-income households and geographic areas. </span></p><p class="cs256F29A0"><span class="cs4457F601">(i) Effective date.</span><span class="cs4F55BD6E"> &mdash; This section is effective upon passage.</span></p>


